<collectorName box="[221,269,619,643]" pageId="11" pageNumber="564">Leg</collectorName>
: 
<collectorName box="[279,386,618,643]" pageId="11" pageNumber="564">J. Daigle.</collectorName>
</materialsCitation>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="564" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1436,222,1543]" pageId="11" pageNumber="564">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,654,679]" pageId="11" pageNumber="564">Remarks.</emphasis>
This subspecies was described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Donnelly" box="[710,896,654,679]" pageId="11" pageNumber="564" refString="Donnelly, T. W. (1992) The Odonata of Central Panama and their position in the Neotropical odonate fauna, with a checklist, and descriptions of new species. In: Quintero, D. &amp; Aiello, A. (Eds.), Insects of Panama and Mesoamerica. Oxford University Press, New York, pp. 52 - 90." type="book chapter" year="1992">Donnelly (1992)</bibRefCitation>
from 
<collectingRegion box="[966,1055,655,678]" country="Panama" name="Panama" pageId="11" pageNumber="564">
<collectingCountry box="[966,1055,655,678]" name="Panama" pageId="11" pageNumber="564">Panama</collectingCountry>
</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[1110,1233,654,679]" name="Costa Rica" pageId="11" pageNumber="564">Costa Rica</collectingCountry>
specimens, based exclusively on the coloration pattern, which is darker than in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="mitratum Williamson" authorityYear="1919" box="[896,1079,692,715]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Heteragrion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="11" pageNumber="564" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="mitratum" subSpecies="mitratum">
<emphasis box="[896,1079,692,715]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="564">H. m. mitratum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1100,1213,690,715]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1959,1981]" captionTargetBox="[203,1397,193,1949]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[203,1397,193,1949]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 7. Heteragrion mitratum mitratum, Maceo: a, female; b, male. H. m. atroterminatum: Anchicayá, pair: c, oviposition; d, copula. Panama, Río Indio: e, male; f, female (Photographs e and f by Benoit Guillon and Dennis Paulson respectively)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1048673/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="564">Fig. 7a–f</figureCitation>
), specially the last abdominal segments (S8–S10) which are completely black in the males (
<figureCitation box="[971,1053,726,751]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1959,1981]" captionTargetBox="[203,1397,193,1949]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[203,1397,193,1949]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 7. Heteragrion mitratum mitratum, Maceo: a, female; b, male. H. m. atroterminatum: Anchicayá, pair: c, oviposition; d, copula. Panama, Río Indio: e, male; f, female (Photographs e and f by Benoit Guillon and Dennis Paulson respectively)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1048673/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="564">Fig. 7e</figureCitation>
), as compared to other subspecies which only present black on dorsum of S10 (
<bibRefCitation author="Williamson" box="[681,883,762,787]" pageId="11" pageNumber="564" refString="Williamson, E. B. (1919) Results of the University of Michigan-Williamson expedition to Colombia, 1916 - 1917. IV. Notes on the species of the genus Heteragrion Selys with descriptions of new species (Odonata). Occasional Papers of the Museum of Zoology University of Michigan, 68, 1 - 89." type="journal article" year="1919">Williamson 1919</bibRefCitation>
). Donnelly was not able to find any significant difference in male caudal appendages. Here, we examined representatives of populations located on the western slope of the Cordillera Occidental, whose male cercus morphology and female intersternite morphology also coincide with those of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="mitratum Williamson" authorityYear="1919" box="[411,586,871,894]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Heteragrion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="11" pageNumber="564" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="mitratum" subSpecies="mitratum">
<emphasis box="[411,586,871,894]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="564">H. m. mitratum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but their face coloration pattern (
<figureCitation box="[976,1089,870,895]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1842,1864]" captionTargetBox="[255,1307,198,1817]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[236,1341,195,1820]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Face color pattern. H. aequatoriale, males: a, Cordillera Central, Santo Domingo; b, Cordillera Occidental, Jericó; c, Cordillera Occidental, Anchicayá; d, Cordillera Central, Carmen de Viboral; e, Cordillera Occidental, PNN Tatamá; f, Cordillera Central, San Luis; g, Cordillera Central, Amalfí; h, female, Cordillera Occidental, PNN Tatamá. H. calendulum: i, male, Santa Cecilia; j, female, Santa Cecilia; k, male Holotype (UMMZ), La Cristalina. H. peregrinum: l, female Paratype (RWG), La Cristalina. H. m. atroterminatum: m, male, Anchicayá; n, female, Santa Cecilia. H. tatama: o, male, PNN Tatamá; p, female, PNN Tatamá. Picture k, by Dr. O´Brien and l, by Dr. Garrison." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1048665/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="564">Fig. 3 k–l</figureCitation>
) are different from both 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Donnelly" authorityYear="1992" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Heteragrion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="11" pageNumber="564" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="mitratum" subSpecies="atroterminatum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="564">H. m. atroterminatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(dark stripe extending from posterior border of head to frontal angle of frons in males, 
<figureCitation box="[1295,1375,906,931]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1959,1981]" captionTargetBox="[203,1397,193,1949]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[203,1397,193,1949]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 7. Heteragrion mitratum mitratum, Maceo: a, female; b, male. H. m. atroterminatum: Anchicayá, pair: c, oviposition; d, copula. Panama, Río Indio: e, male; f, female (Photographs e and f by Benoit Guillon and Dennis Paulson respectively)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1048673/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="564">Fig. 7e</figureCitation>
), and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="mitratum Williamson" authorityYear="1919" box="[151,322,943,966]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Heteragrion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="11" pageNumber="564" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="mitratum" subSpecies="mitratum">
<emphasis box="[151,322,943,966]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="564">H. m. mitratum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(dark stripe more similar but with two projections from vertex to the antennal base in males); these specimens are darker than 
<taxonomicName authorityName="mitratum Williamson" authorityYear="1919" box="[460,637,980,1003]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Heteragrion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="11" pageNumber="564" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="mitratum" subSpecies="mitratum">
<emphasis box="[460,637,980,1003]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="564">H. m. mitratum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in general coloration pattern, as described for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Donnelly" authorityYear="1992" box="[1180,1429,980,1003]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Heteragrion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="11" pageNumber="564" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="mitratum" subSpecies="atroterminatum">
<emphasis box="[1180,1429,980,1003]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="564">H. m. atroterminatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with S8–10 black, and a yellow apical stripe on S8 (
<figureCitation box="[739,849,1014,1039]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1959,1981]" captionTargetBox="[203,1397,193,1949]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[203,1397,193,1949]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 7. Heteragrion mitratum mitratum, Maceo: a, female; b, male. H. m. atroterminatum: Anchicayá, pair: c, oviposition; d, copula. Panama, Río Indio: e, male; f, female (Photographs e and f by Benoit Guillon and Dennis Paulson respectively)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1048673/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="564">Fig. 7c–d</figureCitation>
), making these populations according to Donnelly´s diagnosis a variation of 
<emphasis box="[425,569,1052,1075]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="564">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Williamson" authorityYear="1919" box="[425,566,1052,1075]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Heteragrion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="11" pageNumber="564" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mitratum">H. mitratum</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
closer to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Donnelly" authorityYear="1992" box="[683,929,1052,1075]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Heteragrion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="11" pageNumber="564" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="mitratum" subSpecies="atroterminatum">
<emphasis box="[683,929,1052,1075]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="564">H. m. atroterminatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
than to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="mitratum Williamson" authorityYear="1919" box="[1023,1195,1052,1075]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Heteragrion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="11" pageNumber="564" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="mitratum" subSpecies="mitratum">
<emphasis box="[1023,1195,1052,1075]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="564">H. m. mitratum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Female intersternite (
<figureCitation box="[159,288,1086,1111]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1878,1900]" captionTargetBox="[176,1420,190,1867]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[176,1420,188,1867]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 4. Dorsum of prothorax: a, H. aequatoriale female, PNN Tatamá. H. calendulum Santa Cecilia, b, male; c, female. d, H. m. atroterminatum female, Santa Cecilia. H. tatama PNN Tatamá, e, female; f, male. Female prothoracic intersternite: g, H. aequatoriale, PNN Tatamá; H. calendulum: h, Santa Cecilia; i, Rancho Frío (Panama); j, H. erythrogastrum, La Cristalina; k, H. m. atroterminatum, Santa Cecilia; H. m. mitratum: l, La Cristalina; m, La Fría (Venezuela); n-o, H. peregrinum, female Paratype La Cristalina; p, H. tatama, PNN Tatamá. Pictures l-o by Dr. Garrison." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1048667/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="564">Fig. 4 k–m</figureCitation>
) on these 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Donnelly" authorityYear="1992" box="[408,655,1087,1110]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Heteragrion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="11" pageNumber="564" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="mitratum" subSpecies="atroterminatum">
<emphasis box="[408,655,1087,1110]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="564">H. m. atroterminatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
populations perfectly match the illustrations by 
<bibRefCitation box="[1211,1436,1086,1111]" pageId="11" pageNumber="564" refString="De Marmels, J. (2004) Heteragrion makiritare sp. nov with descriptions of hitherto unknown females and larvae of other species from Venezuela (Odonata: Megapodagrionidae, Lestidae). International Journal of Odonatology, 7 (3), 439 - 458. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 13887890.2004.9748230" type="journal article">De Marmels (2004)</bibRefCitation>
from Venezuelan populations of 
<emphasis box="[526,708,1124,1147]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="564">
<taxonomicName authorityName="mitratum Williamson" authorityYear="1919" box="[526,704,1124,1147]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Heteragrion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="11" pageNumber="564" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="mitratum" subSpecies="mitratum">H. m. mitratum</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
as well as those of the 
<collectingRegion box="[986,1110,1122,1147]" country="Colombia" name="Magdalena" pageId="11" pageNumber="564">Magdalena</collectingRegion>
Valley, and the Panamanian populations of the subspecies 
<emphasis box="[496,712,1158,1183]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="564">
H. m. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Donnelly" authorityYear="1992" box="[568,712,1158,1183]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Heteragrion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="11" pageNumber="564" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="atrolineatum">atrolineatum</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
. With this finding, we expand the geographical range of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Donnelly" authorityYear="1992" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Heteragrion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="11" pageNumber="564" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="mitratum" subSpecies="atroterminatum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="564">H. m. atroterminatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to 
<collectingCountry box="[361,471,1194,1219]" name="Colombia" pageId="11" pageNumber="564">Colombia</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[487,555,1194,1219]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1057,1079]" captionTargetBox="[169,1412,198,1034]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[163,1427,183,1049]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Recorded localities in Colombia for H. calendulum, H. m. mitratum, H. m. atroterminatum and H. tatama." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1048663/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="564">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
). As mentioned under 
<emphasis box="[810,993,1194,1219]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="564">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Selys" authorityYear="1886" box="[810,990,1194,1219]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Heteragrion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="11" pageNumber="564" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aequatoriale">H. aequatoriale</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
further studies are needed to determine if these differences in coloration pattern are just variability within the same species or if they are effective reproductive barriers.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="564" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1436,222,1543]" pageId="11" pageNumber="564">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,298,1302,1327]" pageId="11" pageNumber="564">Biology:</emphasis>
This species inhabits small forest streams with waterfalls in foothills. A pair was observed in copula on the vegetation of a stream at Parque Nacional Farallones de Cali in Anchicayá area. The pair was already in copula at 12:22pm and remained like that until 12:26pm (
<figureCitation box="[806,890,1374,1399]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1959,1981]" captionTargetBox="[203,1397,193,1949]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[203,1397,193,1949]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 7. Heteragrion mitratum mitratum, Maceo: a, female; b, male. H. m. atroterminatum: Anchicayá, pair: c, oviposition; d, copula. Panama, Río Indio: e, male; f, female (Photographs e and f by Benoit Guillon and Dennis Paulson respectively)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1048673/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="564">Fig. 7d</figureCitation>
), then they began ovipositing in submerged live leaves, the male remained beating its wings during the whole time they were ovipositing. At 12:50pm the male abandoned the female (maybe because of our constant disturbance with the camera), and the female remained ovipositing alone at least until 12:56pm, time when we had to leave (
<figureCitation box="[921,1002,1482,1507]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1959,1981]" captionTargetBox="[203,1397,193,1949]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[203,1397,193,1949]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 7. Heteragrion mitratum mitratum, Maceo: a, female; b, male. H. m. atroterminatum: Anchicayá, pair: c, oviposition; d, copula. Panama, Río Indio: e, male; f, female (Photographs e and f by Benoit Guillon and Dennis Paulson respectively)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1048673/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="564">Fig. 7c</figureCitation>
, videos recorded by Camilo Flórez on: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QiZmzWmg53o and https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QRg2fEKl93c).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
